The paper proposes a framework that uses deep learning to learn human design strategies and generate designs without explicit information about objective and performance metrics. This involves interaction with a visual interface and observation of human designers' design state sequences. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning), as the paper heavily relies on deep learning constructs. Additionally, the paper involves image processing, which suggests cs.CV (Computer Vision) as another likely sub-category. The paper also focuses on the interaction between humans and agents, which suggests cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the use of agents to solve a design problem, which suggests cs.SY (Systems and Control) as another possible sub-category.
